BRUEGEL: 'The digging of the Canal between Antwerp and Brussels.' Lost painting (?) only mentioned by Van Mander, see F. Grossmann, Bruegel, The Paintings, p. 20. The picture in the Pulitzer Gallery, certainly XVII C. [later toegevoegd]:(18th Cent.?), may reproduce the lost work, of which perhaps only a drawing existed. The composition would fit in with that of the Winter Landscape with a Bird Trap (1565). The Canal was completed in 1565. Look up [Alexandre] Henne, [Alphonse] Wauters, Histoire de Bruxelles. Baedeker, Belgien, 1930, p. 112 Schon seit der Mitte des XVI. Jh. war Br√ºssel mit dem Rupel, einem Nebenfluss der Schelde, auf dem ? bemerken sind, durch dem 28km langen und 3,2 m tiefen Kanal von Willebroeck verbunden [...]; [verso] p. 119 [...]; p. 170 [...]; What towns appear on the right: Mechelen, Antwerp or Brussels? The canal built between Brussels & Willebroeck. Can one see Antwerp from there? If one is the cathedral tower of Antwerp what is the other? Malines? In order to show the achievement of joining Antwerp to Brussels-Bruegel must have tried to show that Antwerp was visible from the canal. The right tower really looks like that of Antwerp Cathedral. The left one would be what? Many tents (for the labourers!). The church on the left is probably old Walpurgis church, destroyed 1798.To be looked up: Old views of Antwerp. A.J.J. Delen, Iconographie van Antwerpen, [Brussel: L.J. Kruyn], 1930; A.H. Cornette, Iconographie van Antwerpen, [De Sikkel], 1935 [= 1933]. See also catal. Paris, Bibl. Exh. Anvers Ville de Flandre et de Rubens, 1954, pl. 6.
